               <msContents>
                  <summary>This volume contains contains 40 mounted calligraphy specimens in various styles, chiefly by the celebrated Lucknow master <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f2896">Muḥammad ‘Alī</persName>, all mounted on elaborately painted margins. 
                     Swiss mercenary <persName role="pat ins" key="person_7537069" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/7537069/">Antoine Polier</persName> commissioned it as a gift to his friend <persName role="dte" key="person_102326800" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/102326800/">Sir William Jones</persName>, in whose honour it contains an ode on folio <locus>1a</locus>. 
                     The compositions and their arrangement both closely follow another album that Polier also intended for Jones, but kept by its courier <persName  key="person_29571391" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/29571391/">Warren Hastings</persName>, now held in the <orgName>Victorian and Albert Museum</orgName>.
                  </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_10-item1">
                     <author role="com ctb dto" key="person_f2896">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied">Muḥammad ‘Alī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">محمد علی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="pat" key="person_7537069" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/7537069/">Polier, Antoine</editor>
                     <editor role="dte" key="person_102326800" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/102326800/">Jones, Sir William, </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_7971">An Album of Calligraphy</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmalla"/>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>A surviving letter by Polier to Hastings <!-- (cite) --> proves that Polier commissioned this album as a replacement for another one kept by Hastings. See Stronge and Atighi-Moghaddam.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
